rmk:
Le Moineau domestique est l'oiseau commun par excellence. Il est présent dans toute les villes de France et, est majoritairement sédentaire. Originaire d'Europe, il est aujourd'hui présent dans presque la totalité du monde (excepté l'Antarctique). C'est un oiseau peu farouche qui pleinement des Hommes (tel un chat) Il se nourrit de reste de nourriture ou viennent s'approvisionner dans le stock de blé (de quoi facher plus d'un agriculteur). Nos tuiles leurs permettent de faire des bains de soleil et trouve de nombreux endroits pour nicher. Il profite aussi de certains oiseaux pour nicher tel que les hirondelles ou les pics.
La suite sera dans un autre enregistrement.

loc: Santa Rita do Novo Destino, Goiás, Chácara Jayrson

rmk: The clip records a flush of House Sparrows brought about by a false alarm. This, of course, is a regular occurrence among all birds that face the risk of predation constantly. The false alarm was caused by the sudden appearance of a group of wild Rock Doves that flew over a feeding area used by House Sparrows, Starlings and, indeed, the Rock Doves themselves. Hence their arrival in itself caused the smaller birds to react. Not all the House Sparrows fled. Some dived into bushes. Soon all were back out in the open and feeding - as though nothing had happened. The recording opens with calls from a Robin at 0:02 and 0:04; then the Robin broadcasts a series of ticking notes at 0:07 until the end of the ninth second. At 0:15 a Blackbird alarms but, just before that, the first wave of House Sparrows erupt into flight at 0:12.  By 0:15 the remainder explode. By the sixteenth second, a total of 80 House Sparrows have left the ground. Those that did not fly away completely (but are still within the bush) start to 'dust themselves down' and are calling. House Sparrows use a 'meep' call when they are agitated. Often it is doubled into a fast repeat that reminds me of the 'meep meep' of the Roadrunner cartoon bird. Especially from 0:18, a chorus of meep notes can be heard.  Although they are not 'doubled up' on this clip, under other circumstances when just one individual becomes uneasy, it frequently cries wolf with a 'meep meep' that serves as a clarion red alert to all that hear it. In fact, not just House Sparrows react to the signal - but  other birds too.

type: begging call, call, hatchling or nestling
rmk:
**Day 16**. This is one of six recordings made to demonstrate the changing sound of sparrow begging calls. These youngsters were growing up in a nest box that I made this year. It has four compartments, with the central two connected. This family made their nest in the second hole and also used the connected hole three to some extent. Hole four also had a little nesting material inside and hole one appears to have a whole nest inside but was not used; I am not sure when this extra nest was constructed. The nest that they grew up in was mainly made of feathers and moss but unfortunately also contained a strand of plastic from a tarpaulin: sign of our impact on the environment. 

From at least day 15 two young were seen being fed with their heads sticking out of the nest box holes. The adults appeared to hold the food back to get them to lean out further to be fed. Magpies were heard near to the box early on the morning of, I think, day 14 and some may have fledged and been caught. There were two birds remaining which then fledged either on the evening of day 17 or perhaps early in the morning on day 18.

Recording equipment: Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 on tripod. Recording distance 1.5m. All recordings in the series are presented with no editing and the same settings on the recorder (recording level 65). Apologies for the fair amount of background noise, this is what the birds have to put up with too!

This recording was made on "day sixteen". There are other sparrows audible in the background from another nest nearby. The other recordings can be heard at:

day 2: XC483472

file-name: XC331035-2106-08-08 extract village park house sparrow.mp3
rmk:
This was an unattended recording in a tree where house sparrows were quite abundant, located in a park of a rural village, next to a river. There are many calls of the 'follow-me' type, when an adult sparrow wants to be followed by its youngster, usually because the place where they are is not safe or also because they simply should move on to find food, etc. 

The 2-hour recording has been cut leaving only 7 minutes containing the interesting parts. It includes the sound of a previous xenocanto mystery (XC330450), here: 6:40, which is now solved and updated.

I haven't edited the sound much, so I'm sorry if there are urban noises or sometimes low calls, not amplyfied. The 'follow-me' calls can be heard here (they last only one or two seconds): 0:38, 0:46, 0:54, 1:03, 1:21, 1:55, 2:22, 2:40, 2:49, 2:57, 3:12, 3:21, 4:00, 5:34, 5:51, 6:06, 6:40, 6:59, 7:07, 7:33. 

And other unusual calls, also soft but not with the same rhythm: 4:24, 4:52, 5:02.

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: This recording was made with an iPhone 4s with a Sennheiser mic and Røde Rec application. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of these birds' utterances except as detailed above. The entire recording will be made available upon request.

file-name: XC269386-passer domesticus x hispaniolensis brazo del este 12-05-2015.mp3
rmk: el aspecto de estas aves era de gorrión común, Passer Domesticus, salvo por la parte alta de la cabeza más rojiza que denota la hibridación de estos ejemplares con gorrión moruno, Passer Hispaniolensis. Sin embargo sus voces y el hábitat que ocupaba la pequeña colonia, un tarajal cerca de un curso de agua semiseco, eran más propios del gorrión moruno. La hibridación de estas dos especies genéticamente próximas es frecuente y a veces da casos bastante curiosos como éste. El lugar consiste en una serie de plantaciones de arroz, canales de irrigación para éstas cubiertos de vegetación, praderas de almajo y eriales. En aquel momento los canales de riego aún no tenían agua porque no se había plantado aún el arroz, y a causa de la escasez de lluvias primaverales a penas había unos charcones de agua.

Este parque periurbano es una zona que se ha conseguido restaurar con diversas especies de árboles y vegetación riparia que rodea varias lagunas y el cauce de un arroyo. Las grabaciones a veces son más cortas de lo deseado porque el lugar se encuentra muy cerca del aeropuerto de Sevilla, de hecho se pueden ver los aviones aterrizando y despegando desde este parque, y esto perturba los audios. Actualmente este parque está en peligro debido a que se quiere destruír parte de él para hacer una nueva carretera.

UPDATE: After posting the account (below) the identity of this call was sorted out thanks to Herman van der Meer, who suggested that it was a House Sparrow, and Frank Holzapfel, who located another version of the call among his recordings. A great result and I am indebted to both Herman and Frank and I am delighted to have learned something new - and about such a common bird! To follow the saga to its conclusion, it is important to follow the link to the discussion. 

This Starling call has taken almost a year to identify. I heard the sound in the early morning (around 0530hrs on 2 June 2014) and the recording I made of it then already exists as XC187738.  I was trying to record a Collared Dove at the time but my outstretched arm holding black-tipped microphones and a see-through reflector dish infuriated a passing group of Jackdaws and they alighted and gave off merry hell. The rumpus had a knock-on effect on other birds, such as local House Sparrows, who joined in. I was facing the Jackdaws and holding the microphones to best effect. Behind me and coming from nearby back gardens (obscured by houses) came another sound whose delivery suggested that not just Jackdaws and House Sparrows were narked by my presence. The Jackdaws flew off and I looked around for the source of the strange ‘call-to-attention’ piping. By this stage I could not see any other birds in the vicinity. But because the neighbourhood is close to the street where I live, I had a good idea of the possibilities. I could not imagine the call being made by the likes of a Robin, Dunnock, Wren, Blackbird, Blue Tit or Coal Tit. Because Great Tit is such a good mimic, I wondered if that might have been the source. However, even for a Great Tit, the sound was too strong and its varied delivery (sometimes a single note, sometimes a series of up to four distinct repeats) seemed odd. The note had something of the feel of Chaffinch anxiety calls but that too was a bit of a hard argument to swallow.  What about Starling, the master mimic? Unlikely: because the mystery sound seemed not to be any form of imitation. Rather, its purpose and ‘feel’ suggested an alarm note the like of which I had never heard from a Starling. Over the course of the winter of 2014-2015 I heard the same call twice more. Each time the caller was perched strategically and seemed to emit the call - a short burst, then nothing - from tall trees. I was unable to see the bird but I suspected Starling. During the early spring I again heard the sound but this time I could connect Starling with the broadcast. What happened was this: I detected the call a few times in quick succession, looked over neighbouring gardens and saw a Sparrowhawk zooming by in full hunting flight.  With the Sparrowhawk gone, a Starling flew from among a dense growth of ivy encircling a tree trunk.  The sound really could not have come from any other bird. A few weeks later - on 2 April 2015 - I heard the call again. This time I recorded it.  Unfortunately the recording is very poor [XC264943].  Once again, the source was traceable to a Starling, one of which was sitting on a telegraph pole. This time the panic had been caused by a cat. The Starling, I assume, had spotted the predator. Acting as lookout, it called several times, causing all small birds within earshot to react. I could not see the full train of events: so mobbing might have occurred too? Because the call was uttered several times, I (just about) managed to capture its final burst. Finally, in June, I was watching Blackbirds on my lawn when, once again, I heard the call. By now I recognise it. Upon hearing it, the Blackbirds, most of which were adult males (three moulting males, two moulting adult females and a fledged juvenile) dived into undergrowth instantly. Based on their behaviour, they knew the sound as a message to flee. I assume that, as is normal, the juvenile Blackbird fled when the adults did so, thereby learning the importance of the sound.  What was going on? Basically, a low-flying Sparrowhawk had  been spotted by a sentinel Starling. Naturally I wanted to see the Starling utter the sound again. Even though it did not, I am no longer a Doubting Thomas!

I have re-edited the original recording to try and isolate the sound from a cacophony of Jackdaw cackles. The note can be heard at 0:05 (just before the sixth second) and 0:06 (just before the seventh second). At 0:12 a single note is repeated quickly to become four blasts within the thirteenth second [0:13] and start of the fourteenth second.  A fairly clear utterance is at 0:18 and, from 0:21, three blasts occur in fairly quick succession.

in city-habitat -- **sound was trapped for 2 hours** -NO! Bird-SEEN!!  ..... --- 05.11.2017...sunday morning between 07:00-9:15 a clock at my balcony...i tried to record the daily migration-flight of mixed Raven birds.
 -- the Turdus pilaris in district are at this time of the year, foraging here the berries of mountain ash.    ... . the Passer domesticus and the Streptopelia decaocto are through the whole year in my street.    .. and the Tits, the Common Blackbird, the Pica pica and the Wren are to hear (sometimes) in neighbours garden, all seasons, too.
....after about 01:15:00 hours there was excitement of all birds, couse a Hawk tries to hunt there in my district.

loc: cerca del pantano de la minilla, sevilla, andalucía
type: alarm call, begging call, call, flight call
file-name: XC327006-passer domesticus 1-31 cerca del pantano de la minilla 02-06-2016.mp3
rmk: Parte 31 de 31. Una jornada en una colonia de cría de gorrión común ubicada en el puente que cruza un pequeño arroyo en el campo cerca de una explotación de ganado vacuno. Junto a los gorriones se oyen en segundo plano las especies forestales que comparten este hábitat y también el macho residente de ruiseñor común que vive en la orilla del este arroyo. De vez en cuándo algún depredador hace que todas las aves de la zona prorrumpan en llamadas de alarma. Algún mugido esporádico denota la cercanía de las vacas de esta explotación.

De vez en cuándo algún depredador hace que todas las aves de la zona prorrumpan en llamadas de alarma. Algún mugido esporádico denota la cercanía de las vacas de esta explotación.

loc: refugio de la serpiente, estepa, Sevilla, Andalucía
file-name: XC283439-passer domesticus 2 refugio de la serpiente 17-07-2015.mp3
rmk: Desde que se hicieron casas en la zona cada vez hay más gorriones. En un punto de agua a las horas de más calor. Se puede oír gran número de cigarras Cicada Barbara cantando, y muchas abejas Apis Mellifera recogiendo agua. En este refugio se ha restaurado una casa antigua de pueblo, se han plantado árboles y se han instalado comederos, bebederos y una estación de anillamiento. Se están realizando gran cantidad de actividades en el lugar.

El calor ya apretaba y salí a grabar en las peores horas, al mediodía. El motivo era que intentaba grabar una pareja de Falco Tinnunculus que criaba cerca de mi casa y como es una calle concurrida esas eran las horas en las que el nivel de ruido era algo más bajo por la falta de actividad de la gente. Tampoco tenían actividad los cernícalos, que no aparecieron, pero en cambio pude grabar estos gorriones.

loc: cerca del pantano de la minilla, sevilla, andalucía
file-name: XC279046-passer domesticus pantano de la minilla 05-06-2015.mp3
rmk: El ecosistema es un bosque mediterráneo de quercíneas y acebuches con un espeso sotobosque de matorral y salpicado de almacenes agrícolas y construcciones ganaderas. Hay también algunos valles y depresiones más humbríos y cerca un pantano que también tiene algunos eucaliptos.

loc: cerca del pantano de la minilla, sevilla, andalucía
file-name: XC278425-passer domesticus pantano de la minilla 27-05-2015.mp3
rmk: En esta zona hay una población de la especie gracias a los almacenes y establos. El hábitat consiste en bosque mediterráneo de quercíneas y acebuches mezclado con matorral. El suelo es más bien escarpado y hay algunos valles en los que se acumula más la humedad y son de carácter más humbrío. También hay algunos cultivos y la zona está salpicada de construcciones destinadas al ganado, como almacenes, cercados, etc.

Este lugar es un rico mosaico de ecosistemas cuyo cordón umbilical es un cauce de arroyo ahora seco por la falta de lluvias que hemos tenido este otoño. Hay alguna alameda con árboles de sorprendente tamaño, carrizal y tarajal, pero la mayor parte de la vegetación de las orillas ha desaparecido por la acción de los agricultores. Más allá hay una serie de eriales, viñedos, cercados de ganado, pinares, y restos de bosques de quercíneas. Las grabaciones han sido realizadas en un pequeño cauce afluente del arroyo principal que debe tener un manantial por lo cual es el único lugar que ofrece agua disponible en una gran distancia. Por este motivo hay allí montones de pajarillos que por la tarde se congregan para bañarse y beber. Otro motivo es que la vegetación riparia formada por un denso zarzal y zonas de carrizo se ha respetado.

El ecosistema consiste en un cauce de un arroyo seco rodeado por un mosaico de ecosistemas muy diversos. Gran parte de la vegetación riparia ha sido eliminada por los agricultores pero todavía existena lgunas zonas con enormes álamos, tarays y carrizo. Más allá una mezcla de eriales, pinares, bosques de quercíneas, viñedos y alguna granja. Fruto de la sobreexplotación agraria los acuíferos están agotados por lo cual el arroyo madre actualmente va seco, pero ahy un pequeño cauce que sí lleva algo del preciado líquido y que está densamente rodeado de zarzas, álamos, etc. Ahí oculté una de mis grabadoras para rcoger el sonido de cualquier pájaro que pasara por allí.
